          "body": "Having surveyed the world, the Chronicler retracts his lens to trace the single thread of descent from Shem to Abraham (1:17-27). The contrast in texture is deliberate: the Japheth and Ham sections fan outward into peoples and territories; the Shemitic spine contracts inward into fathers and sons, generation by generation, until it arrives at one man: 'Abram, that is Abraham' (1:27). The parenthetical identification of the name-change is the chapter's most charged moment — it is the Chronicler's signal that this is the man of covenant, the recipient of the promises in Genesis 12 and 17. Every name in the long Shemitic chain (Arpachshad, Shelah, Eber, Peleg, Reu, Serug, Nahor, Terah) exists in the chapter for one purpose: to establish that the thread from Shem to Abraham is unbroken. God's faithfulness is not a theological abstraction but a genealogical fact — the line was kept alive, generation by generation, across the entire post-Babel dispersion."
