          "title": "The pastoral payoff for post-exilic readers",
          "body": "Why does a community rebuilding its temple in the ruins of Jerusalem need to begin with fifty-four verses of genealogy reaching back to Adam? Because the exile had functionally severed their sense of identity and continuity. The Babylonian destruction could be read as the end of the story — the covenant had failed, the line was broken, the promises were void. The Chronicler's genealogical prologue is a sustained argument against that reading. The line from Adam to Noah survived the flood. The line from Noah to Abraham survived Babel and the dispersion of the nations. The line from Abraham through Isaac and Jacob survived Egypt, the wilderness, the conquest, the period of the judges, and the divided monarchy. It survived the Assyrian deportation of the northern kingdom. And now, writing after Babylon, the Chronicler insists: the line has survived this too. God has never lost the thread. The names in chapter 1 are not antiquarian trivia — they are the evidence file for the faithfulness of God."
