        "body": "The opening four verses of 1 Chronicles are among the most compressed in the entire Old Testament. Ten names — the antediluvian patriarchs from Adam through Noah's three sons — occupy four verses with no narrative comment whatsoever. In Genesis 5, each of these men receives his lifespan, the name of his son, and the notice that 'he died.' The Chronicler strips all of that away. What remains is the bare genealogical thread: descent, generation by generation, from the first man to the man through whom the race continued after the flood.\n\nThis compression is not laziness; it is theological argument by subtraction. The Chronicler presupposes his readers know Genesis. He does not need to retell the flood — he needs his readers to see the thread that survived it. Adam is not introduced as the first human being who sinned; he is introduced as the first human being from whom the line runs. The fall, the curse, Cain and Abel — none of this appears. The Chronicler's genealogy is not a theology of sin; it is a theology of God's preserving purpose. Through nine generations of mortality, through the catastrophe of the flood, through everything, the line held.\n\nThe naming of Shem, Ham, and Japheth in verse 4 is the chapter's first structural pivot. These three names do not end a genealogy; they open three — the three lines that between them account for every nation in the ancient world (vv. 5-23). The Chronicler is about to demonstrate that the God who started with one man (Adam) is the God of all seventy nations. Before he narrows to Israel, he must show the breadth from which the narrowing comes.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Adam* (v.1) is both a proper name and the generic Hebrew word for 'mankind' — the Chronicler's opening word is simultaneously the name of the first man and the category of all his descendants. The ten names of vv. 1-4 correspond exactly to the antediluvian genealogy of Genesis 5; the Chronicler drops the narrative framework but preserves the order with precision."
