        "excerpt": "The sons of Japheth were Gomer, Magog... Cush became the father of Nimrod; he began to be a mighty one in the earth.",
        "body": "Verses 5-23 summarize Genesis 10's Table of Nations — the most geographically comprehensive passage in the Old Testament, covering peoples from the Aegean coastlands to Ethiopia, from Persia to Arabia. The Chronicler's version is slightly shorter than Genesis 10 (dropping some narrative comments) but preserves the threefold structure: Japheth's line (vv. 5-7), Ham's line (vv. 8-16), Shem's line (vv. 17-23). The order is deliberate: Japheth last in birth order (cf. Genesis 10:21) is listed first; Shem first in covenant significance is listed last, preparing for the Shemitic spine of vv. 24-27.\n\nTwo editorial intrusions break the genealogical monotony and reveal the Chronicler's interpretive hand. First, Nimrod: 'Cush became the father of Nimrod; he began to be a mighty one in the earth' (1:10). In the entire Table of Nations, Nimrod is the only individual singled out for a character description. The word *gibbor* (mighty one, warrior) is the same word used for the *nephilim*-era 'mighty men of old' in Genesis 6:4 and for Nimrod himself in Genesis 10:8-9, where he is called 'a mighty hunter before the LORD' — a phrase that in context describes organized power that operates in God's face rather than under His authority. Nimrod's empire (Babel, Erech, Accad — the cities of Babylonia; then Nineveh and the cities of Assyria, Genesis 10:10-12) represents the institutional origins of the two powers that would most catastrophically threaten Israel. The Chronicler plants this note early: the empires that devastated Israel were not accidents of history. They trace their genealogical and spiritual origin to the Hamitic line's first empire-builder.\n\nSecond, the division in Peleg's days (1:19): 'in his days the earth was divided.' The Hebrew *palag* (divided) is the etymological explanation of the name Peleg. The 'division' refers to the Babel dispersion of Genesis 11:1-9 — God's judgment on unified human hubris, which scattered the peoples and created the ethnic diversity the Table of Nations catalogues. The Chronicler locates this theologically decisive event within the Shemitic genealogy, emphasizing that even the scattering of the nations was God's sovereign act, not a random historical development. Deuteronomy 32:8-9 interprets the same event: 'When the Most High gave to the nations their inheritance, when he divided mankind, he fixed the borders of the peoples according to the number of the sons of God. But the LORD's portion is his people, Jacob his allotted heritage.' The Chronicler's single-sentence allusion to Babel activates this entire canonical background.\n\nThe pastoral significance for post-exilic readers is substantial. The nations that had oppressed Israel — Babylon (descended from Nimrod/Ham), Assyria (also Nimrod's), Persia (from Elam in Shem's line, 1:17) — are all traceable in this Table. They are not ultimate powers; they are branches of a family tree God assembled. Their rise and fall are within His governance. The same God who scattered the nations at Babel is the God who permitted Babylon to exile Israel and then moved Cyrus of Persia (Elam's heir) to release them.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Gibbor* (mighty one, v.10) — the word for a champion-warrior, used of Goliath (1 Samuel 17:51), of David's mighty men (2 Samuel 23), and of God Himself as the 'mighty God' (*El Gibbor*, Isaiah 9:6). Its application to Nimrod carries the irony that his 'mightiness' was the seed of every power that later threatened God's people. *Palag* (divided, v.19) — a rare verb whose use here is entirely explanatory of the name; it occurs again in Psalm 55:9 for the dividing of tongues."
