        "excerpt": "Shem, Arpachshad, Shelah, Eber, Peleg, Reu, Serug, Nahor, Terah, Abram, that is Abraham.",
        "body": "After eighteen verses covering seventy nations, the Chronicler executes the chapter's most dramatic compression: ten names in four verses, tracing the single thread from Shem to Abraham. This is the genealogy of Genesis 11:10-26 stripped of every narrative element — no lifespans, no narrative frame, no mention of other children. Pure descent, nothing else. The effect is like watching a wide-angle satellite image of the whole earth suddenly zoom to a single address.\n\nThe line Shem → Arpachshad → Shelah → Eber is theologically significant before Peleg. 'Eber' is the eponymous ancestor of the 'Hebrews' (*ibrim*) — the ethnic designation that Genesis uses for Abraham's people (Genesis 14:13: 'Abram the Hebrew'). The name 'Hebrew' may derive from *eber* (meaning 'the other side,' referring to those who came from beyond the Euphrates). The Chronicler traces Israel's ethnic designation to this moment in the Shemitic line, before the national boundary of 'Israel' even exists. The people of God have roots in Shem, through Eber, before they are Israelites.\n\nThe line terminates at verse 27 with a notation that is small in size and enormous in significance: 'Abram, that is Abraham.' The parenthetical identification uses both names — the original Abram and the covenant name Abraham ('father of a multitude,' Genesis 17:5). In Genesis 17, the name change accompanies God's covenant of circumcision and the promise of Isaac. The Chronicler's notation assumes the reader knows the covenantal weight of that name change. He is not simply clarifying that two names refer to the same person; he is tagging this man with his covenant identity. Every subsequent narrowing in the chapter — from Abraham to Isaac, from Isaac to Israel — hangs on the covenant that the name 'Abraham' carries.\n\nFor post-exilic readers, the Shemitic spine from Babel's generation to Abraham is a record of God tracking the covenant line across the entire post-Babel dispersion. While the nations were scattering, God was watching one family. While empires were forming, God was preserving one thread. The ten generations from Shem to Abraham are the genealogical equivalent of 'He who called you is faithful; He will surely do it' (1 Thessalonians 5:24).\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Avraham* (Abraham, v.27) — the covenant name from Genesis 17:5, meaning 'father of a multitude.' The Chronicler's notation 'Abram, that is Abraham' (*hu Avraham*) is the chapter's single most explicit theological signal — this is the man of the *berit* (covenant)."
